<TEXT>
the tall men in cowboy boots and western hats 
stalking shoppers in a tokyo meat market were iowa cattlemen 
looking for hints on how to remodel their herds to suit japanese 
tastes 
across town a firm called shop america ltd will soon allow 
japanese to order everything from music to appliances from 
warehouses in new jersey 
difficult though it may be for foreigners to break into the 
japanese market americans see themselves selling tens of millions 
of dollars in goods on the strength of bright ideas quality 
products low prices thorough preparation and government backing 
like the japanese have done for years 
like japan the united states is trying for an economic boost 
through exports and the yenrich japanese consumer is the prime 
target 
this is a huge market the secondbiggest economy in the 
world us ambassador michael armacost said in an interview 
this is an economy where any company in any field that wants to 
be worldclass has got to have a foothold 
many us companies are doing very well in japan armacost 
said but too many still find barriers in local regulations and 
business practices that make it difficult to whittle away at the 
united states 50 billion trade deficit with tokyo 
on thursday us and japanese trade negotiators resume talks 
that aim to change the deeprooted factors in both nations 
economies that contribute to the us trade deficit 
these include japans high savings rate and lower consumption 
high land prices complicated distribution system and corporate 
linkups that tend to leave outsiders in the cold at issue on the 
us side are low savings rates and higher consumption low 
investment the budget deficit and quality of the work force 
the us goal is hoping for more openings to things like shop 
america and us beef those pounding at the door include the us 
retailer toys r us which wants to open big stores in japan but 
is faced with regulations permitting small shops to veto large 
stores nearby 
solomon mester chairman of new yorkbased shop america exults 
in the creation of an atmosphere in japan encouraging sales of us 
goods 
they know they have to import more from the united states 
mester said they know a backlash is building up and they have 
to level the field 
president vernon fraenkel set up shop america with the idea of 
getting the japanese into the us habit of mailorder shopping it 
took more than a year to put together he said and a big problem 
was finding the right japanese partner 
one prospect wanted to stock goods in japan but with high land 
prices it would have been too expensive 
then 711 japan co ltd which has 4000 convenience stores 
came into the picture in august it speedily completed a deal in 
december and expects to open for business nationwide in july 
we had a conservative plan to roll it out suddenly weve got 
a monster with 4000 heads 
the parent company of 711 japan itoyokado co ltd is one of 
the worlds biggest retailers with 12 billion in sales last fiscal 
year 
there are whole teams of people working here on this 
project mester said in an interview at itoyokado headquarters 
shop america will put a computer terminal in each of 711s 
stores customers use a catalog to order small appliances recorded 
music perfume sporting goods watches housewares jewelry and 
other items the barcoded order flashes over a computer network to 
warehouses in new jersey and the goods are sent to japan by mail 
or express delivery 
instead of changing their distribution setup were jumping 
over it mester said 
fraenkel and mester said they set a goal of 20 million in sales 
the first year but 711 japan predicts 70 million 
the shop america executives disbelieve the old saw that the 
japanese wont buy american goods even if theyre cheaper us 
beef is finding ready buyers here at prices sometimes 50 percent 
below the cost of japanese beef 
under pressure from washington japan agreed in 1988 to increase 
its quota on beef imports gradually until 1991 when the import 
limits will be abolished tariffs will be in place until 1994 
if we dont attempt to satisfy this market other parts of the 
world will satisfy it said marshall king chairman of the iowa 
cattlemens association 
king of boone iowa was one of four iowa cattlemen and a meat 
scientist from iowa state university who were exploring japanese 
tastes 
jim bradford of guthrie center iowa vice chairman of the iowa 
beef industry council said the information would help cattle 
breeders plan the right kind of steer for japan a fiveyear 
process 
the iowans visited a fivestory seiyu supermarket where posters 
with iowa gov terry branstads photo beckoned shoppers to try 
iowa quality beef 
