<TEXT>
nearly 16000 utah teachers were told 
monday to prepare for a strike in a dispute with state legislators 
centering on salary increases and better benefits 
thousands of teachers spent their presidents day holiday monday 
at a rally in the utah capitol sponsored by the utah education 
association 
we are still negotiating association president jim campbell 
said after a threehour closeddoor meeting monday night with 
members of his board we are still having teachers stay on a 
strike alert but we will not call a strike tomorrow morning 
teachers were told by officials of the union to report as usual 
to classrooms tuesday campbell would not comment further 
state lawmakers following recommendations in republican gov 
norm bangerters 11 billion education budget pumped 12 million 
into textbooks and offered to enable local school districts to 
impose higher property taxes to help relieve classroom overcrowding 
they also promised to dedicate the lions share of a 150 
million 198990 budget surplus to education but remained steadfast 
in offering educators only a 6 percent salary increase the same as 
other public employees and balked at dipping into utahs 48 
million rainy day fund or repealing a tax cut imposed last 
september 
the nearly 16000 members of the education association voted 
3to1 friday to reject the proposed raise they also authorized 
the education associations 16member board to call a strike if 
their demands are not met by the time the republicancontrolled 
legislature adjourns its regular session at midnight wednesday 
teachers want the legislature to increase the amount it 
appropriates for education but have not demanded a specific amount 
utah house speaker nolan karras who has been involved in 
negotiations spoke briefly with campbell on monday and said house 
republicans will consider the situation in caucus tuesday morning 
a strike could affect up to 420000 students and utahs 20000 
teachers 
teachers point to their average salary of about 25000 which 
ranks 41st in the nation they contend utah has the largest class 
sizes in the country and spends the least per student 
the education association called a statewide oneday strike in 
september after the legislature approved a 35 million tax cut but 
no new money for education 
