<TEXT>
this cant really be the oldfashioned 
neighborhood pool hall that mothers warned their sons to stay out 
of 
there at the bottom of the menu is the polite admonition 
shootz cafe is a smokefree environment thank you for not 
smoking 
minnesota fats could shed a few pounds at the shootz a yuppie 
bistro and billiards lounge where the customers chalk their cues 
over california wine spritzers or chow down on gazpacho and a 
heaping antipasto of imported cheeses prosciutto sundried 
tomatoes and artichoke hearts 
this is a clean upscale billiards hall no smoke no 
drunks says coowner ric adamcik its where mothers can tell 
their sons and daughters to go and have a good time in fact you 
can bring your mother along 
a former army brat adamcik remembers sneaking into pool halls 
outside the gates of military bases for a forbidden peek at the 
pinepaneled maleonly world where players sucked on longneck buds 
and jostled with hustlers and bookies over the seductive click and 
thump of billiard balls on green baize 
it was the kind of place where a guy could scratch spit and 
talk dirty all night long without a nagging whine from the missus 
i remember that i didnt want to play in a place that smelled 
like that adamcik said it stank of stale beer and cigarettes 
it was so smoky it made my eyes burn it was full of guys with 
packs of camels rolled up their sleeves and momma tattoos on 
their arms 
the cue racks at the shootz cafe hang on raspberry walls the 
hightech stereo system blasts new wave music earnest young 
professionals in starched buttondowns power ties and wide 
suspenders bend over 14 topoftheline brunswick tables of oak and 
brass 
for that homey feel adamcik says players awaiting their 
turn can relax on leather sofas around a roaring fireplace 
billiards industry officials say the oldtime pool halls are 
dying out they have fallen victim to soaring rents local 
antivice ordinances and staterun lotteries that have lured 
customers away from poolrooms that frequently served as fronts for 
illicit gambling enterprises 
more important the growing affluence of americans has produced 
a dramatic change in the way they spend their leisure time says 
mark cord executive vice president of the billiard congress of 
america the industrys trade association 
people dont want to spend the evening alone in a dingy place 
where theres a lot of drinking and gambling cord said 
families are staying home or going out and doing things together 
smart business owners are making money by appealing to the family 
trade at a respectable place 
cord says an estimated 35 million americans are playing 
billiards regularly a 430 percent boost since the mid1950s that 
makes it the second most popular family sports activity in the 
united states after bowling he says 
the yuppie elegance of the shootz cafe is applauded by such 
billiards greats as willie mosconi and minnesota fats who fondly 
remember the fabulous era of chandeliered salons in new york 
chicago detroit and other cities in the 1920s before poolrooms 
turned into gambling dens during the great depression 
mosconi 76 who lives quietly in suburban philadelphia won 15 
world billiards titles before he retired from tournament play nine 
years ago 
minnesota fats whose real name is rudolph wanderone and was 
portrayed in the movie the hustler by the late jackie 
gleason is over 90 still fat and still shooting pool 
i can beat anybody on earth wanderone said in a telephone 
interview from the nashville tenn hotel where he lives 
tipping the scales at 200 pounds wanderone says his appetite 
knows no bound not even gazpacho and artichoke hearts 
im not a picky eater he said ill eat anything that 
dont bite me first 
