<TEXT>
efforts to predict the effects of global 
warming are being hurt by lack of access to 40 years of secret 
soviet and us military data on the north polar ice cap 
scientists said 
submarine sonar measurements of the thickness of the ice cap are 
crucial to understanding ocean currents underneath the ice cap 
said michael schlesinger of oregon state university 
those currents must be understood if researchers are to predict 
accurately the rate of warming of the earths climate as carbon 
dioxide is released into the atmosphere schlesinger said monday at 
the annual meeting of the american association for the advancement 
of science 
what i want is month by month the thickness of sea ice 
which you can only get by submarine schlesinger said 
soviet military planners have the same data on the north polar 
ice cap that american military officials have schlesinger said 
but his soviet colleagues have told him they cannot get the secret 
data 
satellite measurements of the monthly changes in the size of the 
ice cap are available but the satellites cannot be used to measure 
the ices thickness he said 
schlesinger is one of a small number of researchers developing 
computer programs to simulate the effect of global warming and 
predict its future consequences 
such models need data on ocean currents to make accurate 
predictions he said there are five such models in the united 
states and the same number in the soviet union he said 
all the models have run with some assumption of this missing 
term under the ice he said 
syukuro manabe another developer of such models said the ocean 
can absorb a lot of the heat produced as increasing amounts of 
carbon dioxide in the air trap more and more of the suns heat 
researchers said they do not yet know exactly how much heat the 
oceans can absorb 
the amount of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere is expected to 
double by the first half of the next century but the associated 
warming will probably lag by several decades because at first the 
heat will be lost into the oceans said manabe a researcher at a 
national oceanic and atmospheric administration laboratory at 
princeton university in new jersey 
the eventual temperature rise is expected to be an average of 2 
degrees to 4 degrees around the world the researchers said 
manabe hopes the abatement of the cold war will help 
globalwarming researchers 
im hoping that this will be one of the peace dividends he 
said that the us and the soviets will exchange sea ice data 
