<DOCNO> AP900220-0032 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
polluted snow from acid rain may be 
killing off salamanders in the colorado rockies one of a series of 
mysterious population declines among amphibians around the globe a 
researcher said 
scientists fear the decline of frog toad and salamander 
populations even in relatively pristine national parks may 
presage ecological disaster 
amphibians are tough critters said david wake director of 
the museum of vertebrate zoology at the university of california at 
berkeley they survived whatever wiped out the dinosaurs and 
they have thrived through the age of mammals if they start to 
check out now we better take it seriously 
an 8year study by john harte a professor at the university 
indicates a link between declines of hardy 6inch tiger 
salamanders in the rocky mountains and an increase in the acidity 
of ponds in which they live 
hartes study noted that snow formed from acid rain melted in 
the late spring pouring into 14 ponds he studied and raising their 
acid level 
the study found acid levels such as those created by melting 
snow severely disrupted egg growth and killed developing salamander 
embryos harte said monday 
studies in the eastern united states have shown the impact of 
acid rain on fish populations but hartes study is the first 
strong evidence that the same problem may be hitting the west the 
university said in a statement 
harte collaborated on the project with erika hoffman a 
scientist at the lawrence berkeley laboratory 
the study was presented at a special meeting called by the 
national research council at the national academy of sciences 
beckman center in irvine in southern california scientists were to 
meet through today to discuss declining amphibian populations a 
global phenomenon 
amphibians are coldblooded moistskinned creatures who spend 
part of their lives in the water and part on land declines in 
local populations on six continents were first noted in the late 
1970s 
in the past few years drastic population declines have been 
noted in such species as the golden toad in costa rican rain 
forests the yellowlegged frog in the sierra nevada and spotted 
frogs in the northwestern us which now are being considered for 
addition to the endangered species list 
suggestions about the cause of declines in specific populations 
range from acid rain and other water pollution to disease 
exploitation for food and climactic changes 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

