<TEXT>
stormie jones the 12yearold recipient of 
the worlds first heartliver transplant underwent a second liver 
transplant early tuesday because of damage from hepatitis 
a team of surgeons began the operation around 315 am said 
liz mcmahon a spokeswoman for childrens hospital 
the surgery was expected to last 12 to 16 hours said another 
hospital spokeswoman margy buczynski 
the doctors arent expecting many complications because she is 
in good condition ms buczynski said 
stormie and her mother lois purcell flew to pittsburgh from 
their home in white settlement texas on monday 
the surgery is necessary because stormies first donated liver 
no longer functions normally due to damage from hepatitis said liz 
mcmahon another hospital spokeswoman 
ms buczynski would not identify the donor of the new liver 
stormies heartliver transplant on feb 14 1984 was done by a 
medical team led by transplant pioneer dr thomas e starzl starzl 
will be present for part of the latest operation but dr andreas 
tzakis will lead the team ms buczynski said 
the first transplant took 16 hours the donated heart and liver 
came from a 4yearold girl who died in a new york car accident 
before the double transplant stormie had suffered two heart 
attacks and undergone two triple coronary bypass operations 
she suffered from a rare congenital disease which increased to 
10 times normal the level of cholesterol in her blood the 
imbalance was caused by a faulty liver 
stormie was leading a fairly normal life until october 1988 
when she was readmitted to childrens hospital for possible organ 
rejection she improved the next month after surgeons removed a 
bile duct obstruction but was back again in january 1989 because 
of elevated enzyme levels that interfered with her antirejection 
medication cyclosporine 
the girl started losing liver function in november and returned 
to the hospital once again starzl replaced her cyclosporine with 
an experimental japanese drug fk506 believed to be 50 to 100 
times more powerful with fewer side effects 
stormie returned to childrens hospital on jan 6 with more 
liver problems tests showed no evidence of organ rejection but 
rather a noninfectious form of hepatitis 
surgeons followed stormies 1984 operation with two more 
attempts at heartliver transplants but both patients died within 
a few days of surgery 
those were the only attempts in america at replacing the heart 
and liver in a simultaneous operation until dec 3 when pittsburgh 
surgeons performed the worlds first heartliverkidney transplant 
the patient cindy martin 26 of archbald remains in critical 
condition in the intensive care unit at presbyterianuniversity 
hospital 
ms martin also is receiving fk506 and has experienced no 
organ rejection 
