<TEXT>
a nearterminally ill woman implanted with 
an artificial lung device died about 15 hours after surgery 
a team of anesthesiologists and surgeons at the penn state 
university center placed the device known as the intravascular 
oxygenator in the woman at noon sunday the university said the 
unidentified women died of pneumonia at 3 am monday 
dr michael t snider director of the study at the milton s 
hershey medical center said the device helped sustain the 
34yearold womans life during the hours it was used 
this was a woman with a nearterminal disease snider said 
unfortunately her disease was too far advanced to save her 
it was the second clinical trial of the experimental device 
melicia harvey 16 of arthur city texas died feb 7 of lung 
failure she lived 4 days on the device known as ivox which had 
functioned normally after her operation at lds hospital in salt 
lake city 
the device mimics the lungs ability to filter carbon dioxide 
out of the blood and replace it with oxygen it was designed to 
give damaged lungs time to rest and recover 
the food and drug administration has approved experimental use 
of the device for up to seven days in patients with respiratory 
problems 
before the lungassist device mechanical ventilation has been 
the only method to help patients who have trouble breathing 
the device is a 20inch bundle of hundreds of synthetic tubes 
almost as fine as human hair with walls so thin that oxygen and 
carbon dioxide can pass through 
it is inserted via the neck or groin into the inferior vena 
cava the large vein that brings blood to the heart 
two tubes the diameter of a soda straw are attached to the 
bundle of tubes and lead out of the body one delivers oxygen to 
the blood while the other removes carbon dioxide 
 
jd mortensen a thoracic surgeon and vice president for 
research at cardiopulmonics inc in salt lake city conceived the 
ivox and developed it 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

