<TEXT>
the grounding of three cargo ships 
along the stretch of coral reefs off the florida keys has led to an 
agreement by owners of 60 oil tankers to keep six miles away from 
the fragile reefs 
fifteen of the nations largest oil companies agreed monday to 
put more distance between their tankers and the 200milelong 
barrier reefs to guard against grounding and oil spills said gov 
bob martinez 
the coral reefs will be a much safer place martinez told 
reporters there were no spills from the three groundings last fall 
some 60 tankers regularly transit the straits and about 250 
other vessels occasionally passing through will stay outside the 
buffer zone some tankers carry as much as 21 million gallons of 
cargo 
the agreement which takes effect april 1 will increase the 
cost of traveling the route said amoco transport co president ed 
roland but the buffer zone will give cleanup crews considerably 
more time to contain a spill 
he could not estimate the extra costs roland who is chairman 
of the marine transportation committee of the american petroleum 
institute called the agreement a major step in further 
safeguarding the southern florida environment 
under the agreement the ships will stay 10 nautical miles or 
12 statute miles from the shoreline and five nautical miles or 
six statute miles from the edge of the shallow reefs 
ships sailing from the atlantic ocean into the gulf of mexico 
often hug the corral banks to avoid the strong fueleating 
currents of the gulf stream 
twentyfive percent of the tanker traffic will be more 
seaward than it is today martinez said 
