the british investigation team comprises superintendent john 
troon and inspector graham dennis of scotland yard and dr ian 
west the government said late monday 
the move was seen in part as a government attempt to allay fears 
of a coverup since kenya gained independence the murders of 
three prominent politicians have gone unsolved and the former 
kenyatta government was accused of covering them up 
scotland yard is the commonly used name for the london police 
kenya is a former british colony and its security personnel 
continue to receive training from britons 
ouko disappeared one week ago apparently without telling 
colleagues or family members his disappearance was reported two 
days later 
the government on monday said pathologists found a bullet hole 
in the 58yearold ministers head 
in a statement it said police also found a 38caliber revolver 
near oukos right hand and the central firearms bureau which 
licenses guns identified the weapon as belonging to the minister 
near his body police also found a gas can and a plastic bag 
containing a pair of jeans a shirt and a leather jacket the 
jacket pockets contained four bullets and kenyan currency 
equivalent to 18 
the clothes were identified as belonging to ouko and a storeman 
said the gas can resembled one previously stored at the ministers 
home the statement said 
ouko was considered one of the most articulate and able members 
of president daniel arap mois cabinet he first served as 
permanent secretary in the foreign ministry in 1963 when kenya 
gained independence from britain 
ouko later held other highranking government jobs before being 
tapped by moi to head the foreign ministry in 1979 
