<TEXT>
the supreme court today allowed the federal 
government to withhold highway funds from states that do not comply 
with a national speed limit 
the court without comment rejected an appeal by nevada 
officials who want to set the speed limit at 70 mph on some state 
highways 
congress established a 55 mph national speed limit in 1973 in 
response to the arab oil embargo the law was aimed at conserving 
oil although it also was endorsed as a safety measure 
the limit was raised to 65 mph in 1987 for rural highways that 
move blunted most protests primarily from western states over the 
55 mph limit 
the 1987 law affects about threefourths of the 43000mile 
interstate system and makes another 7000 miles of federal state 
and local highways eligible for the 65 mph limit 
most states raised the speed limit to 65 mph on affected rural 
roads after congress allowed it 
the nevada legislature in 1985 increased the states limit to 70 
mph and in 1986 that limit was posted on a 33mile stretch of 
interstate 80 but the higher speed limit was withdrawn when 
federal officials threatened to cut off highway aid to the state 
nevada officials then sued in federal court saying the state 
had no real choice but to comply with the national speed limit 
because otherwise it would lose about 95 percent of its highway 
funds 
the state officials said the national limit violates the 
constitution by coercing compliance by the states 
the 9th us circuit court of appeals last august rejected the 
states arguments 
the impropriety of making judicial judgments regarding a 
states financial capabilities renders the coercion theory highly 
suspect the appeals court said 
it noted that nevada one of several states with no income tax 
could increase its tax revenue to make up for a cutoff in federal 
funds 
moreover the appeals court said congress could order states to 
adhere to a national speed limit not merely cut off funds for 
noncompliance 
the appeals court relied in part on a 1987 supreme court ruling 
that upheld a federal law threatening to reduce highway aid to 
states that refused to adopt a minimum drinking age of 21 
the case is nevada vs skinner 89686 
</TEXT>
