<TEXT>
colorado lost a highstakes fight today with 
the federal government over money and other property seized from 
drug traffickers as the supreme court refused to hear the states 
appeal 
the justices without comment let stand a ruling that the 
proceeds of drug transactions automatically are forfeited to the 
federal government in the case that had been appealed the 
government later transferred nearly all the money to local police 
departments 
the case involved 15 million in cash and gold bars colorado 
attorney general duane woodward had contended that a states claim 
on such money and property to satisfy owed taxes sometimes should 
take precedence 
police in lakewood colo seized the cash and 12 gold bars from 
the home of albert and victoria levy during a nov 21 1982 search 
the money and gold were the proceeds of a cocaine deal 
the next month state tax authorities assessed taxes totaling 
194000 against albert levy based on alleged narcotics sales of 
almost 3 million in 1982 
a state judge ruling on a tax lien imposed said the money 
could come from the seized proceeds 
federal authorities meanwhile went into a federal court in 
denver seeking forfeiture of the seized loot they said a 1978 law 
gave the federal government a superior claim to the proceeds 
because forfeiture dates back to the commission of the crime 
us district judge john kane jr ruled that part of the states 
tax lien should be paid from the cocaine deal proceeds but justice 
department lawyers appealed his ruling 
the 10th us circuit court of appeals last april 21 reversed 
judge kanes ruling and ordered that all the proceeds be forfeited 
to the federal government 
the appeals court ruled that the 1978 law permits a federal 
claim to seized drugtrafficking proceeds at the time a crime was 
committed which always will come before a states attempt to 
attach a tax lien 
in the states appeal woodward said the appeals court ruling 
unduly interferes with state taxing powers the appeal also argued 
that the federal forfeiture law was permissive not mandatory 
bush administration lawyers urged the court to reject the 
states appeal noting that congress in 1984 amended the law to say 
explicitly that the interest of the united states vests at the 
time of the act giving rise to the forfeiture 
they argued also that the forfeiture law is mandatory 
last october judge kane ordered the cash and gold bars released 
to the federal government last dec 7 us attorney general dick 
thornburgh authorized transfer of about 90 percent of the forfeited 
propertys value to five police and sheriffs departments in 
colorado 
the lakewood police department received the bulk 63 percent of 
the revenuesharing transfer 
the case is colorado v us 89699 
