<TEXT>
the supreme court today let stand a ruling 
that shields government social workers from being sued for placing 
children in foster homes where they are sexually abused 
the justices without comment refused to review a federal 
appeals court ruling that the social workers enjoy absolute 
immunity if their childplacement decisions were approved by a 
court 
in a decision that set a legal precedent for nine western 
states the 9th us circuit court of appeals said social workers 
in such cases share the absolute immunity that shields judges 
prosecutors and others in judicial proceedings 
the scope of such judicial immunity was the sole issue before 
the high court in a case from washington state 
the justices last october let stand a different federal appeals 
courts ruling in a maryland case that children who are abused by 
foster parents may not sue the government social workers who placed 
them in those homes 
in that case the appeals court did not rely on immunity 
instead it ruled that child abuse by foster parents is private 
not governmental violence 
the supreme court last year ruled that public officials may not 
be sued in federal court when their alleged gross negligence 
permits a child to be abused by a parent what the court called 
private violence 
that decision said a state has no constitutional duty to protect 
people including abused children who are not in the states 
custody but it left undecided whether a constitutional duty exists 
to protect children from foster parents chosen by government 
officials 
in the case acted on today two caseworkers with the washington 
department of social and health services were sued by three sisters 
who said they were repeatedly raped sodomized and sexually 
assaulted by their foster father over an 18month period in 198283 
the girls were ages six eight and 12 when the attacks allegedly 
began 
the foster father lee michael subsequently was convicted of 
statutory rape and indecent liberties he is serving a 55year 
prison sentence 
michael was the girls uncle the girls mother who committed 
suicide in 1978 was a sister to michaels wife 
the girls civil rights lawsuit named social workers wanda tyler 
and mark bronson as defendants the suit alleged that the social 
workers had violated the girls interest in being free from harm 
while in state custody 
ms tyler in the spring of 1982 placed one of the girls all of 
whom were then residing with their fathers parents in richland 
wash with michael bronson who took over the case from ms 
tyler placed the two other girls with michael shortly thereafter 
a federal trial judge refused to dismiss the suit but the 9th 
circuit court reversed that ruling last sept 6 
finding the social workers role to be an integral one in the 
judicial process the appeals court said they are entitled to 
absolute immunity 
in the appeal acted on today lawyers for the girls noted that 
most foster care placements are courtapproved and involve periodic 
court reviews federal law bars states from obtaining federal 
reimbursement for foster care if the placements are not 
courtapproved 
the appeals court ruling is binding law in washington arizona 
alaska california hawaii idaho montana nevada and oregon 
the case is babcock vs tyler 89912 
