<TEXT>
the supreme court today made it easier for 
disabled children to win some federal welfare benefits 
by a 72 vote the justices struck down a government regulation 
that gave children seeking the benefits less protection than adults 
the bush administration said the decision could force officials 
to reevaluate benefits for more than 250000 children 
the court ruled in favor of disabled children seeking what is 
called supplemental security income from the department of health 
and human services 
the benefits are provided to the disabled of all ages an adult 
is considered disabled if he or she is unable to engage in any 
substantial gainful activity by reason of any medically 
determinable physical or mental impairment lasting at least a 
year 
children under 18 are considered disabled if they suffer from 
any medically determinable physical or mental impairment of 
comparable severity 
the definitions were interpreted by hhs officials in a way that 
made it more difficult for children to qualify 
if an adults mental condition does not meet one of those listed 
in hhs regulations he or she is entitled to an individual 
assessment to determine the extent of the functional impairment 
but the hhs rule struck down today did not permit such 
individual determinations for children 
the bush administration said treating adults differently makes 
sense because they are evaulated with regard to their ability to 
work 
but justice harry a blackmun writing for the supreme court 
said a similar analysis can be used with regard to children 
an inquiry into the impact of an impairment on the normal 
daily activities of a childis no more amorphous or unmanageable 
than an inquiry into the impact of an adults impairment on his 
ability to performgainful work blackmun said 
chief justice william h rehnquist and justice byron r white 
dissented 
the case stemmed from an appeal by brian zebley of pennsylvania 
who suffers from congenital brain damage that has caused 
retardation and other problems the government cut off the 
supplemental benefits when the boy turned 4 in 1982 
justice department officials said a victory for the zebley boy 
could force hhs to reevaluate more than 250000 cases in which 
children have been denied benefits between 1983 and 1988 hhs 
estimated the cost of the reevaluations alone would be more than 
41 million 
the case is sullivan vs zebley 881377 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
