<TEXT>
a centuryold tradition of maleonly 
membership at two princeton university eating clubs could end 
within a year 
tiger inn one of the last two allmale eating clubs voted 
monday to end its policy of excluding women from membership 
the vote came less than a week after ivy club the only other 
allmale institution on the central new jersey campus voted in 
favor of admitting women 
under club rules a final policy change at each club requires a 
second confirming vote in one year which must then be approved by 
each clubs graduate board made up of alumni 
the ivy club and the tiger inn are the last two of the schools 
13 private eating establishments that do not admit women most 
juniors and seniors take their meals at the clubs which are housed 
in private homes near the campus 
despite pressure from opponents of the allmale policy many 
undergraduate women have attended the clubs which allow women to 
visit and use their facilities but not to join 
i think women go there to allmale clubs because of their 
laidback attitude sophomore julie slattery said we always 
have fun at their parties 
tiger inn president mike salerno said the decision to admit 
women would enhance the club some here decided this day and this 
year that it will be a positive change he said 
news of the vote pleased opponents of the maleonly policies 
im really happy and surprised said jen weiner a junior 
who directs the coalition for coeducated eating clubs i was 
concerned that there would be some backlash because of ivys 
decision in that the members might want tiger to remain the last 
bastion of allmaleness 
the two clubs have maintained their maleonly positions for 11 
years in the face of a sex discrimination lawsuit filed by sally 
frank a princeton graduate 
ms frank filed a lawsuit against three eating clubs that 
continued to deny membership to women after the university began 
admitting female students in 1969 the other 10 voluntarily opened 
their doors to women after the school went coed 
cottage club the third eating club originally sued by ms 
frank voted to end its discriminatory practices in 1986 and 
settled with ms frank for 20000 
the university was originally named in the suit but also settled 
in 1986 paying ms frank 27500 in legal fees and pledging to 
disassociate itself from sexually segregated clubs 
in may 1987 the new jersey division on civil rights ruled in 
ms franks favor and ordered tiger inn and ivy club to admit 
women however the superior court of new jersey appellate division 
reversed that decision in october 1988 due to procedural errors 
following the clubs appeal the case is pending in the new jersey 
state supreme court 
