<TEXT>
the government is looking into whether to 
enlist swarms of caterpillars in the war against cocaine in peru 
and bolivia by setting them loose to eat coca plant leaves 
officials said today 
but a spokesman for national drug policy director william 
bennett emphasized that the program is in the experimental stage 
and that any unleashing of the caterpillars would have to be 
approved by the peruvian and bolivian governments 
the updated national drug control strategy released jan 25 
seeks 65 million for agriculture department research in fiscal 
year 1991 starting oct 1 a 5 million increase over the 15 
million to be spent this year 
the washington post which first reported on the plan in todays 
editions described the program to develop chemical and biological 
agents to destroy drug crops as secretive 
however bennetts spokesman don hamilton said its out 
there in the strategy its in the budget documents if we didnt 
look into this stuff i think wed be irresponsible 
hamilton stressed that the united states is not considering 
biological warfare against anyone or anything 
these are experimental programs looking at all drug plants to 
try and learn as much as we can about them including herbicides 
and natural enemies of the plants he said this isnt 
something that is an option yet its a prospect of an option 
the proposed experiments he said would have to show that one 
of these things was safe and effective and then you would have 
to talk to the governments involved and see if theyre interested 
until you do that you dont have anything the spokesman said 
the post said the principal focus of the effort is the malumbia 
a white moth that in its caterpillar stages eats the leaves of the 
coca plant 
growers in perus upper huallaga valley where more than half 
the worlds cocaine originates douse their crops with insecticide 
to kill the native malumbia caterpillars 
the newspaper said researchers believe that if they could breed 
the insect in mass quantities hundreds of millions of malumbia 
eggs or caterpillars could be airdropped over the cocagrowing 
regions thwarting the growers efforts at crop protection 
waldemar klassen associate deputy administrator for the 
agricultural research service told the post this is quite a 
voracious caterpillar if we could put them down there in 
sufficient number we could then defoliate the plants 
klassen was not immediately available to discuss the report 
both klassen and program leader larry christy were in meetings this 
morning according to aides 
the post reported that there has been no public disclosure of 
the project and one official told the newspaper he was reluctant 
to discuss it for fear of upsetting latin american leaders 
hamilton denied that the research was secret adding that 
general outlines were included in the strategy update and 
accompanying budget document 
the strategy does not specifically mention the caterpillar 
experiments or provide details of research plans but it notes 
great advances have been made in agriculture through the 
development of biological agents to enhance or reduce the 
productivity of various crops such endeavors may also have 
applicability to various aspects of the drug war 
the strategy says this is the reason for the 5 million increase 
in the agricultural research service drug budget request and says 
the research findings would be shared with and be made available 
to foreign governments 
the drug strategy budget summary document says the 5 million 
would be used in part to support increased research and 
development on nonherbicidal methods of control 
president nixon encouraged work on a biologically engineered 
worm during the height of the heroin epidemic in the 1970s more 
recently scientists have been working on an herbicide to kill 
drugproducing crops both efforts were not been carried forward 
because of political resistance by latin american governments 
were not looking for some magic bullet here hamilton said 
even if the caterpillar successfully wiped out coca crops he said 
youve still got other drugs this doesnt end everyones 
problems by any stretch of the imagination 
</TEXT>
