<TEXT>
new yorks highest court today upheld child 
pornography charges against an albany man in a case involving only 
the purchase of pornography not its distribution or production 
but the court disappointed prosecutors by stopping short of a 
precedentsetting decision that could have outlawed the possession 
of child pornography throughout the state 
the court of appeals decided 70 that albany county prosecutors 
had properly secured a fivecount indictment against william keyes 
for promoting a sexual performance by a child 
a lawyer for keyes 41 contended that although keyes bought the 
magazines and videotapes with titles including wonderboy and 
lolita colour special 7 from undercover police officers he had 
not procured the magazines and videotapes under the meaning of 
the state antipornography statute 
to fall under the law albany lawyer terence kindlon argued 
keyes would have had to arrange for underage models to appear in a 
pornographic performance or he would have had to sell the items 
himself to other people 
the court rejected those arguments 
in a decision by judge fritz alexander iii the court concluded 
that the state legislature clearly meant for the purchase of child 
pornography to fall under the acts covered by the word procure 
when creating the statute a decade ago 
alexander said the statute is directed at the consumers of 
child pornography as well as at its manufacturers and 
distributors 
however the court did not make the kind of blanket antichild 
pornography pronouncement that prosecutor george barber had hoped 
it would make 
alexander did call child pornography a social evil but 
because keyes was charged with promoting the items rather than 
possessing them alexander said it was not necessary for the court 
to address the question of whether possession of child pornography 
is constitutionally protected 
thirteen states have explicitly outlawed possession of child 
pornography and barber said he had hoped the court today would 
remind new yorks legislature that it could follow suit 
keyes an auto body worker and partially disabled vietnam war 
veteran faces a maximum of 3 to 7 years in prison on each of the 
five counts he had been on 5 years probation for a conviction for 
promoting a sexual performance by a child at the time of his arrest 
</TEXT>
