<TEXT>
the supreme court today rejected the appeal of 
a georgia school district ordered to pay lawyer fees incurred in 
administrative hearings by a couple who won a free and 
appropriate education for their handicapped daughter 
the court without comment let stand a ruling that the federal 
law guaranteeing educational opportunity for handicapped youngsters 
authorizes such lawyerfee awards 
lawyers for the muscogee county school district had argued that 
lawyer fees may be awarded only when parents who invoke the federal 
law prevail in court not in administrative proceedings 
the school district lawyers told the justices that federal 
appeals courts are divided over the issue of awarding lawyer fees 
incurred in administrative hearings 
the muscogee county controversy began when paige mitten a 
13yearold girl with cerebral palsy partial blindness and mental 
retardation moved with her family to columbus ga in 1985 
paige had been attending public schools in texas where an 
individualized education plan was developed for her 
county school officials refused to permit paige to enter the 
public school system or to develop a new individual education plan 
for her instead they recommended she be placed in a staterun 
center in columbus 
paiges parents objected to placing her in the center but did so 
on a temporary basis 
at an administrative proceeding in late 1985 a regional hearing 
officer ruled that the school district violated the federal 
education of the handicapped act by not providing paige with the 
required free and appropriate education 
school district officials appealed but a state hearing officer 
upheld the regional hearing officers findings 
but the state hearing officer also concluded that the mittens 
would have to sue in federal court in their attempt to recover 
legal fees incurred in their fight to get paige an education 
a federal judge ruled that no lawyerfee awards are available 
under the handicapped childrens protection act for administrative 
proceedings but the 11th us circuit court of appeals reversed 
that ruling last july 20 and ordered the judge to determine how 
much the school district should pay 
the school district then sought supreme court review 
the case is muscogee county school distict vs mitten 89905 
