<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to decide 
whether prosecutors who exclude blacks as jurors because of their 
race violate the rights of white defendants 
the justices said they will review the case of a white ohio man 
larry joe powers convicted of two murders by a state court jury 
after seven blacks who could have served as jurors were excluded 
the high court in 1986 ruled that when prosecutors disqualify 
potential jurors based on their race it violates the 14th 
amendments guarantee of equal protection 
but that case involved a black defendant and black jurors the 
court never has said whether unlawful racial discrimination in jury 
selection occurs when the defendant is of a different race than the 
excluded jurors 
in a decision announced jan 22 however five of the courts 
nine justices implied that excluding blacks as jurors because of 
their race does discriminate unlawfully against white defendants 
the court in that decision ruled that a separate right the 6th 
amendment guarantee of an impartial jury is not violated when 
prosecutors exclude blacks as jurors if the defendants are white 
although it was not an issue in the case five justices 
thurgood marshall william j brennan harry a blackmun john paul 
stevens and anthony m kennedy seemed to agree that such 
racebased exclusions do violate any defendants 14th amendment 
right 
powers was convicted of the july 27 1985 murders in columbus 
of gary golden and thomas kicas he was sentenced to 50 years to 
life in prison 
during jury selection at the trial powers lawyer objected to 
the prosecutions exclusion of the seven black jurors the 
presiding judge overruled the objections 
a state appeals court upheld the convictions 
the case is powers vs ohio 895011 
</TEXT>
