<TEXT>
here at a glance are highlights of actions 
taken tuesday by the supreme court 
 
jailed mother 
 
the court ruled that parents suspected of child abuse may be 
jailed indefinitely for refusing to disclose the whereabouts of 
their children 
the justices said societys need to protect children from harm 
generally outweighs a parents constitutional right against 
selfincrimination 
by a 72 vote the court upheld the indefinite jailing of a 
maryland woman until she tells authorities where her young son can 
be found 
the case is baltimore department of social services vs 
bouknight 881182 
 
social workers 
 
the court let stand a ruling that shields government social 
workers from being sued for placing children in foster homes where 
they are sexually abused 
the justices without comment refused to review a federal 
appeals court ruling that the social workers enjoy absolute 
immunity if their childplacement decisions were approved by a 
court 
the case is babcock vs tyler 89912 
 
speed limit 
 
the court allowed the federal government to withhold federal 
highway funds from states that do not comply with a national speed 
limit 
the justices without comment rejected an appeal by nevada 
officials who want to set the speed limit at 70 mph on some state 
highways 
the case is nevada vs skinner 89686 
 
disabled children 
 
the court made it easier for disabled children to win some 
federal welfare benefits 
by a 72 vote the justices struck down a government regulation 
that gave children seeking the benefits less protection than 
adults the bush administration said the decision could force 
officials to reevaluate bendefits for more than 250000 children 
the case is sullivan vs zebley 881377 
 
drug money 
 
the court handed colorado a defeat in a highstakes fight with 
the federal government over money and other property seized from 
drug traffickers 
the justices without comment let stand a ruling that the 
proceeds of drug transactions automatically are forfeited to the 
federal government in the case that had been appealed the 
government later transferred nearly all the money to local police 
departments 
the case is colorado vs us 89699 
 
jurors 
 
the court agreed to decide whether prosecutors who exclude 
blacks as jurors because of their race violate the rights of white 
defendants 
the justices said they will review the case of a white ohio man 
larry joe powers convicted of two murders by a state court jury 
after seven blacks who could have served as jurors were excluded 
the case is powers vs ohio 895011 
 
challenger suit 
 
the court refused to revive a lawsuit by the widow of one of the 
seven astronauts who died when the space shuttle challenger 
exploded in 1986 
the court without comment left intact a ruling that shields 
the federal government and a nasa engineer from being sued 
navy commander michael j smith was one of the seven killed when 
the challenger exploded 74 seconds after its jan 28 1986 launch 
his widow jane sued for damages and to bar morton thiokol 
manufacturer of the shuttles booster rockets from bidding on any 
future national aeronautics and space administration projects 
the case is smith vs us 89607 
 
south africa 
 
the court let stand baltimore md ordinances requiring the 
citys public employee pension plans to withdraw all investments in 
companies doing business with south africa 
the justices over one dissenting vote rejected a challenge 
that said the divestment ordinances among other things 
impermissibly intrude on the federal governments power to conduct 
foreign relations 
the case is lubman vs mayor and city council 89889 
 
scientologists 
 
the court left intact a ruling that drastically limits the right 
of authors to quote unpublished material such as diaries and 
letters 
the court without comment refused to hear an appeal by a 
company that published a biography attacking the late l ron 
hubbard founder of the church of scientology 
the 2nd us circuit court of appeals in a ruling last april 
that was denounced by scholars publishers and freespeech 
advocates imposed strict limits on the use of quotations from 
unpublished material 
the case is holt vs new era publications 89869 
</TEXT>
