<TEXT>
the campaign has been contentious 
filled with threats and accusations of foul play but international 
observers say chances are good that sundays election will be clean 
credibility is a critical issue in an election that amounts to a 
referendum on a decade of sandinista rule 
both sides rely on the observers to ensure a fair election but 
for different reasons 
president daniel ortega and the sandinistas expect to win and 
approval by the observers will lend legitimacy the united national 
opposition whose presidential candidate is violeta barrios de 
chamorro says only international observers will keep the 
sandinistas from cheating 
more than 1000 observers are fanning out by jeep boat plane 
and horseback to watch the election from the first votes cast to 
the last counting 
one of the most visible observers is jimmy carter the former 
us president who denounced cheating in last years panamanian 
election while the votes were being counted his prestige and anger 
helped destroy the credibility of the election which gen manuel 
antonio noriega later nullified 
the largest observer missions are from the organization of 
american states which has 450 people and the united nations with 
200 
nicaragua is the first country to invite un election 
observers sandinista officials hope a verified victory will bring 
better relations with washington and international aid for an 
economy ravaged by mismanagement war with ussupported contra 
rebels and a us economic embargo 
a credible election can be the foundation for getting us out 
of this crisis said adolfo beteta spokesman for the supreme 
electoral council there has never been an election with more 
observers 
since the sandinistas overthrew president anastasio somoza in 
1979 nicaraguas economy has shrunk by more than half wages have 
fallen to less than 10 percent of their former value and private 
consumption is down by 70 percent the currency was devalued 39 
times in 1989 
officials of the un and oas observer missions and a 
representative of carters council of freely elected heads of 
government have been in nicaragua for months 
they have mediated disputes about opposition access to 
statecontrolled media use of government resources by the 
sandinistas intimidation campaign violence and many other 
subjects 
i expect a clean election but if there are irregularities on 
a large scale we will be able to detect them said jennifer 
mccoy head of the carter mission 
leonel zuniga of the oas said his observers plan to visit 2500 
of the nations 4391 polling places many unofficial observers 
will help from us congressmen to church workers 
between the oas and the other observers i would guess almost 
100 percent of the polling places will be covered zuniga said 
we hope for and we expect a clean election 
to keep them from voting more than once citizens will have to 
dip their fingers in bright blue ink that takes days to wash off 
to prevent stuffing of ballot boxes each precinct will be assigned 
a number chosen by poll watchers when it opens and the number will 
be stamped on every ballot 
ballots will be counted twice once at the precinct and at one 
of nine regional centers international observers will watch the 
counting at many precincts and all regional centers 
the un and the oas missions will get copies of the returns 
and will do their own sample counts to check against official 
returns 
some potential problems still exist voter identification cards 
do not bear photographs and each side accuses the other of buying 
cards stealing them or duping people into giving them up 
leaders of the opposition alliance known as uno express 
concern that their poll watchers will be frightened into resigning 
before the election but say they expect to have people at about 95 
percent of the voting stations 
