<TEXT>
the nuclear regulatory commission announced 
today that it will decide on march 1 whether to license the 
seabrook nuclear power plant setting the stage for an intense 
legal battle 
the commission is expect to approve the licensing and 
challenges to that decision are considered certain 
plant spokesman ron sher said preparations for fullpower 
operation would begin immediately after a license is issued he 
said the gradual ascension to fullpower commercial operation would 
take two to three months although the plant would produce a small 
amount of electricity within a month 
a key question for whatever court handles the promised appeals 
to a license would be deciding whether to stay operation of the 
plant pending resolution of the appeals 
the 64 billion plant the scene of huge antinuclear 
demonstrations in the late 1970s and 1980s was completed in 
mid1986 it has remained idle for lack of a federal operating 
license mainly because massachusetts officials contend that the 
safety of people living around the plant could not be assured in 
case of a major accident 
the federally mandated 10mile emergency planning zone around 
the 1150megawatt reactor includes six massachusetts communities 
challenges to a license also allege flaws in emergency plans for 
new hampshire towns 
seabrook critics including massachusetts attorney general james 
shannon have said the issuance of a license by the nrc is a 
foregone conclusion and that the real fight will be in court 
shannon and others argue that while nrc officials have deemed 
emergency evacuation plans for seabrook adequate to protect the 
public safety the commission has never spelled out its definition 
of adequate 
commission chairman kenneth carr said in january that such broad 
issues would not be addressed in the nrc decision on seabrook carr 
said the decision will instead focus on specific issues directly 
relating to the plant 
a 1979 new hampshire law targeted at seabrook bars utilities 
from charging their customers for unfinished and canceled power 
plants 
unable to bill customers for seabrook and faced with repeated 
cost increases and delays seabrooks main owner public service 
company of new hampshire entered bankruptcy reorganization two 
years ago a proposed settlement calls for public service to be 
acquired by connecticutbased northeast utilities 
