<TEXT>
health secretary louis sullivan continued his 
campaign against tobacco companies tuesday and issued a report 
showing that smoking costs the country more than 52 billion 
annually in health care costs and lost productivity 
sullivan condemned tobacco company advertising practices that 
target women minorities and young people saying they must stop 
their irresponsibility 
in testimony before the senate labor and human resources 
committee he also called on advertising agencies to join 
antismoking efforts by renouncing tobacco ads and said television 
stations should donate free air time to help educate viewers about 
the dangers of smoking 
sullivan also said that while the bush administration supports 
the intent of legislation to increase regulation of tobacco 
products and educate about the risks of smoking it believes the 
bill which would cost an estimated 185 million is unnecessary 
the tobacco product education and health protection act of 1990 
would establish a center as part of the federal centers for disease 
control to expand education efforts on smoking conduct 
smokingrelated research and regulate tobacco products much as the 
food and drug administration regulates food products 
the center also would administer a paid advertising program to 
discourage smoking and provide incentive grants to states to 
encourage enactment and better enforcement of laws prohibiting the 
sale of tobacco to minors 
sullivan said his department yearly spends about 79 million on 
antismoking programs many of which duplicate the efforts proposed 
in the legislaton 
he said free public service announcements about the risks of 
smoking are preferable to governmentpaid ads in light of other 
demands on the federal budget he also said that regulating the 
additives in cigarettes envisioned in the bill would send the 
wrong message 
were concerned that this would suggest that we believe that 
under certain conditions with certain monitoring that tobacco is 
safe he said we would rather see our efforts on reducing and 
elmiminating by the year 2000 all tobacco from our society 
however sen edward kennedy dmass and chairman of the senate 
committee noted that bottled perrier water was pulled from the 
market when it was found to contain benzene at levels up to four 
times what is allowed under federal standards while a surgeon 
generals report estimated the benzene content of cigarettes is 
2000 times higher than that 
the consumer has a right to know the key ingredients and 
additives to a pack of cigarettes when they purchase the product 
kennedy said 
sullivan agreed that consumers should have such information 
charles o whitley representing the tobacco institute noted in 
testimony submitted to the committee that congress previously 
considered and rejected disclosure of ingredient information 
because it contains trade secrets this information is supplied to 
the health and human services secretary but it does not identify 
the company or brand of cigarettes 
whitley also said other provisions in the bill arent needed 
because young people are already aware of the risks of smoking he 
also denied that the industry targets young people in advertising 
campaigns to encourage them to take up the habit 
he also defended the industry against critics who say that 
tobacco companies target women and minorities saying the industry 
is not trying to encourage people to start smoking but rather hopes 
to retain or gain market share from competitors 
sullivan released a report on the economic consequences of 
smoking that estimated smokingrelated disease costs each american 
221 a year largely in healthcare and insurance costs 
he said the costs average 1 billion per state annually but 
range from a high of 58 billion in california to a low of 82 
million in alaska the reports analysis the first of its kind is 
based on 1985 statistics 
smoking causes an estimated 390000 deaths in the united states 
annually and about 29 percent of adults smoke he said 
sullivan recently criticized rj reynolds tobacco co for its 
plans to market a cigarette targeted at blacks reynolds 
subsequently dropped those plans but now intends to testmarket a 
cigarette called dakota news accounts have said the company was 
considering gearing the cigarette toward young women with a high 
school education or less 
sullivan has been concerned about minorities because they have 
higher rates of smoking than whites and have a higher rate of 
smokingrelated disease and death among high school seniors the 
smoking rate has leveled off at around 19 percent he said while 
lung cancer has surpassed the incidence of breast cancer among 
women 
</TEXT>
