<TEXT>
the bush administration under pressure to 
speed up its savings and loan cleanup said tuesday it will borrow 
11 billion by the end of march for its thrift bailout agency 
the new money should start flowing to the resolution trust corp 
by the end of this month said william taylor the chief staff 
officer of a treasuryled board overseeing the agency 
without the money the rtc would face a cash crunch that would 
virtually halt the disposal of failed thrifts after this week 
according to rtc spokesman stephen j katsanos 
bailout legislation enacted in august provides 50 billion 
through next year to cover the losses of failed thrifts but the 
trust corporation needs to borrow as much as an additional 100 
billion in working capital 
the 11 billion is the first leg of the borrowing which is to 
be repaid as the government sells loans real estate and other 
assets inherited from the failed thrifts 
the agency hasnt announced its borrowing plans for subsequent 
quarters but taylor said the amount in the apriljune period 
could be more than 11 billion 
tuesdays announcment follows a ruling last week by the justice 
department which found the rtc a government agency eligible to 
borrow through the treasury although the trust corporation is 
overseen by a treasuryled panel its work is performed by an 
independent banking agency the federal deposit insurance corp 
members of congress and private analysts have harshly criticized 
the arrangement as bureaucratic and prone to delays however the 
establishment of the new borrowing plan likely will shift the brunt 
of pressure from the administrations oversight board to the fdic 
were going to try to stay out of their way as much as 
possible taylor told reporters 
federal reserve board chairman alan greenspan a member of the 
oversight panel told a house banking subcommittee tuesday he 
expected a significant acceleration of activity 
at the end of last week the rtc had disposed of only 49 of the 
368 failed thrifts it has seized the agency has made little 
headway in selling the 180 billion in assets owned by the sampls 
it is projecting an increase in resolutions to 50 institutions 
per quarter approximately double the pace of its first six months 
of operation 
