<TEXT>
a pentagon report released tuesday said that 
the air force colonel who resigned last week as editor of the 
pacific stars and stripes newspaper violated military regulations 
by manipulating the papers news content 
col edwin j montgomery resigned friday citing the report by 
ombudsman philip foisie 
foisie was hired by the defense department last year to assess 
the free flow of information to the military readership of the 
toykobased pacific stars and stripes and its european sister 
publication based near frankfurt west germany 
montgomery had said he was disappointed that foisie viewed his 
editing practices as news management but was pleased he had not 
been accused of censorship 
in his report foisie said that the editing process at pacific 
stars and stripes under montgomery was seriously flawed but 
that there was no censorship in the sense of readers being 
systematically deprived of any specific type of news 
in my professional judgment col montgomery has too often 
infringed on the common practice of good journalism foisie 
wrote if censorship is the wrong word news management is 
probably the right description of these infringements and it is 
expressly prohibited in the military regulations 
civilian journalists at pacific stars and stripes have publicly 
complained of censorship by military editors news management and 
harassment of journalists who raise objections 
foisie said montgomery who assumed the role of commander and 
editorinchief of the newspaper in 1986 was seriously miscast 
due to a lack of journalistic experience and had failed to delegate 
many editing duties 
foise credited montgomery with improving the newspapers 
financial position and said some of montgomerys critics on the 
paper had exaggerated the news management problem by claiming 
he frequently killed stories unfavorable to the military 
but foisie said montgomery was preoccupied with the details of 
editorial content and had introduced what many staff journalists 
consider an ideological element in deciding which stories were 
printed and how they were displayed in the paper 
this foisie wrote has had a chilling effect on the staff 
and has induced a degree of selfcensorship 
foisie said the tokyo newsroom had fallen into disarray and was 
plagued by very low morale an incipient staff revolt and one 
might say a staff conspiracy 
reiterating a recommendation he made in a preliminary report 
last month foisie said the newspaper should put a civilian in the 
post of top news executive that would make the paper less 
vulnerable to charges that the military censors it he said 
the stars and stripes papers are authorized but unofficial 
publications the pentagon says their charter says they are to 
provide a free flow of news and information without 
censorship or news management 
