<TEXT>
social security commissioner gwendolyn king on 
tuesday defended the agencys nationwide tollfree telephone 
network as a success story but acknowledged that callers too 
often get busy signals 
mrs king said the agency was preparing television and newspaper 
public service announcements encouraging people to have breakfast 
with social security by calling between 7 and 9 am when lines 
are less busy 
the telephone network which went nationwide in october was 
expected to handle about 250000 calls a day but more than 15 
million people try to get through on peak days and many call 
between 10 am and 2 pm she said 
the 800 number is the biggest success story weve had mrs 
king said at a media briefing we just have too a big a success 
on our hands the trick is how to manage it so that it works 
better 
the telephone network reached by dialing 18002345ssa is 
staffed from 7 am to 7 pm local time across the country and 
allows callers to take care of many matters without going into a 
social security office 
however congressional critics have complained that people often 
are unable to get through on the tollfree lines and that many 
dont get full and accurate information when they do get through a 
house ways and means subcommittee was scheduled to hold a hearing 
wednesday on the network 
mrs king said a study by the inspector generals office of the 
department of health and human services found that 67 percent of 
those who used the tollfree line said they would use the telephone 
again to do business with social security up from 53 percent in 
1984 
eightytwo percent of those who contacted social security using 
the 800 number reported the service was good or very good she said 
what we are finding is that when people do get through they 
find the service is courteous theyre very happy with the 
information they received she said 
in january traditionally a busy month for the agency an 
estimated 52 percent of calls to the tollfree number were met with 
busy signals compared with 14 percent in december 51 percent in 
november and 30 percent in october mrs king said her goal is to 
reduce the busy rate on peak days to 35 percent by the end of the 
year 
mrs king also announced three steps to improve morale and 
service at the social security administration where many workers 
have complained that they are overworked and unable to provide good 
service because of huge staff cuts during the reagan administration 
mrs king said she is 
dispatching four strike teams to visit field offices 
throughout the country and approve additional employees and 
equipment where needs are the greatest about 400 employees could 
be added she said 
suspending all numerical performance goals such as handling a 
certain number of cases per day or per month mrs king said the 
agency would come up with a new set of goals to better measure 
workloads and performance 
naming bill rogers a former social security employee from the 
seattle area as ombudsman to hear complaints and ideas from social 
security managers and employees 
