<TEXT>
in an effort to save africa and europe from a 
pest that once plagued the western hemisphere the house 
agriculture committee on tuesday approved a bill allowing sale of 
sterile screwworms to other countries 
sterile screwworm flies mate with fertile screwworm flies but 
produce no offspring causing the population to eventually 
disappear 
through intensive efforts the pest was declared eradicated in 
the united states in 1982 the government has spent millions of 
dollars to kill it off in mexico and central america so it doesnt 
return to the united states 
the discovery of the pest in north africa causes deep concern 
because it potentially could spread to the middle east and southern 
european nations bordering the mediterranean sea said rep kika 
de la garza chairman of the agriculture committee 
the screwworm fly is a flesheating parasite that attacks all 
warmblooded animals even humans and is a serious threat to 
livestock 
de la garza said that in countries such as those in north 
africa where drought and famine have weakened human health people 
are abnormally vulnerable to the insect 
this could lead to the need for additional requests for food 
aid and public health assistance in a region already burdened with 
over 140 billion in external foreign debt he said 
he said that shortly after the screwworm was discovered in 
africa the un food and agricultural organization asked the joint 
usmexico screwworm commission to help 
the only facility mass producing sterile screwworms has been 
operated since 1976 by the commission in tuxtla gutierrez mexico 
the usda agriculture department reports that it is possible 
the screwworm could become the most devastating livestock and 
wildlife pest on the african continent said de la garza this 
bill would provide the necessary authority for the usda or the usda 
working through the commission to sell sterile flies to the food 
and agricultural organization 
the legislation is not controversial and is supported by the 
bush administration though the senate has not yet acted speedy 
movement through congress is anticipated 
</TEXT>
