political reform in the soviet union and 
eastern europe has made the soviet kgb spy agency less 
confrontational but the threat from foreign spies will decline only 
modestly for now the head of the cia said tuesday evening 
i think the kgb has become less confrontational in the sense 
that they avoid doing blatant or flatfooted things that would 
create a major press issue the cia director william webster 
said in remarks prepared for delivery to the baltimore council on 
foreign affairs but the activity is there and it will continue 
the agency released a text of his remarks in washington 
within the soviet union however there does seem to be a 
movement toward relaxing kgb repression of soviet dissidents 
webster said noting a similar withering of internal secret police 
activity among the kgbs allied spy agencies in eastern europe 
webster predicted the eastern european agencies would reduce 
their cooperation with moscow but that no major reduction in their 
effort to gain us secrets would occur so long as the warsaw pact 
remains in place 
he also said that as economic competition replaces political 
and military tension between east and west attempts to acquire 
sensitive technology by all nations is increasing and becoming 
more sophisticated 
webster presented a complicated picture in eastern europe where 
spy agencies have operated since world war ii as proxies for the 
kgb 
their subservience to the kgb and gru soviet military 
intelligence is due for careful review he said 
he noted that the hungarian foreign ministry publicly 
disassociated itself recently from the alleged spying efforts of 
us army sgt clyde lee conrad arrested in west germany in 1988 
on charges of spying for a hungarian intelligence officer 
the foreign ministry declared it an erroneous policy pursued 
by the previous leadership without regard to the countrys national 
interests webster said 
but the intelligence chief cautioned that espionage and 
counterintelligence are widely recognized in eastern europe as 
necessary functions and the apparatus for this work is likely to 
remain in place the work will continue 
the warsaw pact he said requires that east european 
intelligence services cooperate with the soviet union so i dont 
expect military intelligence collection efforts to abate 
certainly not in the near future 
overall he said his agency hopes that new political leadership 
in eastern europe will reduce some hostile intelligence activity 
such as passing sensitive technology to the soviets an activity 
which is incompatible with requests for us loans but fundamental 
changes in intelligence missions are not likely while the warsaw 
pact treaty connections are still in place 
in addition he said the current spy managers in east europe 
were picked from the old communist loyalists and trained in the 
soviet union and may be difficult to replace 
webster said all the changes would ultimately depend on the 
success of soviet leader mikhail gorbachevs efforts to put the 
soviet union on the road to a more democratic government 
but the new system he is trying to create is not yet ready to 
take the place of the old one he is discarding webster added 
economic conditions have deteriorated crime is increasing 
ethnic turmoil is escalating 
whether gorbachevs responses will satisfy the soviet people 
quite frankly we dont know and neither do they 
he also outlined two separate rates of political change in east 
europe 
profound transformation is going on in hungary 
czechoslovakia east germany and poland where communist parties 
are in full retreat webster said but in the balkans the 
process of transformation is more complicated 
political opposition is not welldeveloped in many of these 
