the general assembly convened its first 
special session on narcotics tuesday with major drugproducing 
nations and major drugconsuming nations seeking to forge an 
international battle plan for the 1990s 
the fourday session is expected to shift the previous emphasis 
on stopping drug production in poor countries to a more balanced 
approach which includes fighting consumption in wealthier nations 
it is expected to consider wider issues of distribution 
marketing and money laundering the related arms trade and sale of 
manufacturing chemicals 
secretary of state james a baker iii told the session the 
most critical challenge facing the united states in combating 
narcotics abuse is the problem of domestic consumption 
as long as the demand for drugs by americans remains 
voracious our nation faces an endless uphill struggle to halt 
supply baker said 
a text of his prepared remarks was released by the state 
department 
the debate began with colombian foreign minister julio londono 
paredes telling the 159nation assembly that for too long the 
burden in the drug fight has been borne by a small number of 
developing nations 
action must be taken on many fronts he said including action 
against the production of manufacturing chemicals and against 
corrupt officials and increased aid to developing countries to 
reducing the demand for drugs 
paredes said colombia believes that to fight drugs there must be 
sustained growth in the producing countries and that requires the 
creation of jobs external financing and easier access of exports 
to external markets 
international cooperation is necessary he said but he 
emphasized the responsibility of each state to control drug 
trafficking responsibility also must include respect for the 
sovereignty of other states he said without using drug traffic as 
a lever for applying economic pressure 
the session with more than 100 speakers is an effort to 
develop a blueprint for international cooperation against illegal 
drug supply demand trafficking and distribution 
un officials said the session would not focus on production by 
poor third world nations where many farmers have little choice in 
cultivation but would look at a broad spectrum of issues the 
session aims to enhance the effectiveness of un agencies in the 
battle against drugs and seek more money for them 
mexicos attorney general enrique alvarez del castillo called 
drugs the universal social disease the plague of the modern 
world 
but he said mexico is opposed to the creation of all 
multinational military or paramilitary forces and added the 
sovereignty of peoples and territorial integrity are not open to 
discussion multilateral cooperation should rest on the principle 
of respect for the rights of others 
del castillo said his government supports application of an 
international legal framework 
he said it was pointless to debate whether producing or 
consuming nations were more to blame we all are responsible 
he said 
he noted that mexicos drug consumption is relatively low 
regular users numbering only about 8 percent of the population 
mostly urban youth 
brazils foreign minister roberto de abreu sodre said the 
focus has been on production of illegal drugs but today there is a 
greater understanding that effective action must address many 
facets from cultivation to consumption 
elimination of illicit crops he said only can be achieved 
through integrated programs of rural development that provide 
economically viable alternatives 
there also is growing concern to address the problem of the 
covert flow of arms to drug traffickers and to curb the 
participation of mercenaries in drugrelated criminal activities 
in his address baker expressed hope that a unled effort to 
act against drug smuggling will help the world come closer to 
ending the drug scourge 
he added that to be successful any such program must entail 
concrete commitments and be fully implemented by un agencies 
certainly we the member governments cannot ask the united 
nations to do things that we will not do at home he said 
bakers appearance at the session five days after the drug 
summit in colombia was aimed at reinforcing the high priority the 
bush administration is attaching to the drug issue 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

