<TEXT>
the senate on tuesday opened discussion of a 
contentious resolution remembering armenian genocide amid 
potential strains in usturkish relations and a rift between some 
republicans and the bush administration 
the resolution which would set april 24 as a day of remembrance 
of the armenian genocide of 19151923 is sponsored by senate 
minority leader bob dole rkan 
about 15 million armenians died during the period victims of 
the ottoman empires attacks on the ethnic group the ottoman 
empire is now turkey 
its time for the united states officially to commemorate 
the armenian genocide dole said on the floor of the senate 
for too long we have ignored history for too long we 
have failed to speak the truth about the tragedy of genocide 
it is time finally for all of us to do what is right 
turkey a nato ally is fiercely opposed to the measure and has 
objected to the term genocide to characterize what happened to 
armenians during the period 
turkish prime minister turgut ozal made his views known in 
meetings last month with dole and other senators 
i am deeply concerned that if the senate passes the 
resolution it will unwittingly slap the face of a very important 
nato ally said sen robert byrd dwva an opponent of the 
resolution and the only senator to speak against it tuesday 
he said passage of the measure could jeopardize the upcoming 
round of negotiations on base rights 
the turks already have banned ports of call by us 
nuclearpowered warships and barred flights by training missions 
into a gunnery range according to mike mcnamara who represents 
turkey 
byrd called genocide a specific legal term as defined by the 
geneva convention 
i do not know whether what happened to the armenians 
constitutes genocide he said whatever happened was wrong he 
said 
discussion was expected to continue until thursday when the 
senate is scheduled to vote to cut off debate with a cloture vote 
sixty senators are needed to end talk so a vote can be taken 
dole had 61 cosponsors when he introduced the resolution last 
year however the measure now has only 46 cosponsors 
what has changed is the launching of a massive lobbying effort 
against the resolution by the administration by the government 
of turkey by american businesses who operate in turkey and 
regrettably by some private organizations and individuals who 
ought to be supportive of the resolution 
the bush administration has publicly opposed the resolution 
although george bush indicated during the 1988 presidential 
campaign that he would be inclined to remember victims of the 
armenian slaughters 
sen paul simon dill quoted bush as saying in 1988 that the 
united states must acknowledge the attempted genocide of the 
armemians i would join congress in commemorating the victims of 
that period simon quoted bush as saying 
clearly a different signal is coming from the white house 
today simon said 
dole who said he was not trying to embarrass the turkish 
government said he is willing to introduce legislation to ban any 
possible reparations to the armenians 
