<TEXT>
interior secretary manual lujan on tuesday 
announced appointments of four state officials and three leaders of 
conservation organizations to be initial members of the new north 
american wetlands conservation council 
two interior department officials are exofficio members of the 
council formed by legislation last year to guide the purchase of 
wetlands important for migratory birds 
the legislation carries out a 1986 agreement between the united 
states and canada aimed at improving 6 million acres of wetlands in 
both countries the new council will recommend acquisitions and 
other projects to the existing migratory bird conservation 
commission mexico agreed in 1988 to cooperate with the effort 
president bush has said he wants a goal of no net loss of 
wetlands 
the new appointments 
peter f bontadelli director of the california department of 
fish and game 
gary meyers executive director tennessee wildlife resources 
agency 
w alan wentz undersecretary of the kansas department of 
wildlife and parks 
james a timmerman jr executive director south carolina 
wildlife and marine resources department 
matthew b connolly jr executive vice president ducks 
unlimited 
john c sawhill president of the nature conservancy 
william w howard jr executive vice president and chief 
operating officer of the national wildlife federation 
john f turner director of the interior departments fish and 
wildlife service and charles h collins executive director ot the 
national fish and wildlife foundation are exofficio members of 
the council 
terms are for three years but to arrange staggered terms wentz 
and sawhill will serve two years and timmerman and howard will 
serve one year 
