<TEXT>
president bush on tuesday presented the first 
charles stark draper award to two texas engineers who developed the 
semiconductor microchip an invention that helped america change 
the world 
jack s kilby and robert noyce working separately in the 1950s 
developed the microchip also known as the integrated circuit 
integrated circuits have enabled us to do the unimaginable 
bush said at an awards ceremony at the state department now it 
is unimaginable to believe we could ever live without them 
the microchip helped america change the world 
the integrated circuit incorporates a large number of 
transistors on a single tiny piece of silicon 
kilby is chief technical officer of the houston area research 
center noyce is president and chief executive officer of austins 
sematech a research consortium of high technology companies 
the two men who are recognized by the scientific and 
engineering community as independent coinventors of the monolithic 
integrated circuit will share the 350000 award 
the draper award for engineering achievement is sponsored by the 
national academy of engineering it was established in 1988 with an 
endowment by the cambridge massbased charles stark draper 
laboratory 
the prize will be awarded every two years to individuals who 
have contributed significantly to the advancement of engineering 
and whose achievements have produced important benefits to the 
wellbeing and freedom of all humanity 
bush said the microchip in addition to transforming everyday 
life with such items as computers and calculators has stirred 
the new breeze of democracy across the world 
during a visit tuesday with vaclev havel the new president of 
czechoslovakia bush said he thought about how the microchip had 
helped provide images that linked the peoples of prague and 
warsaw budapest and berlin images of bravery and defiance of 
humanitys quest for freedom 
and it was the microchip which carried those images from one 
nation to another becoming an instrument of liberty and the symbol 
of the information age 
microchips are used in products ranging from medical equipment 
to calculators and watches their invention provided for storing 
and manipulating information in a very small space replacing the 
need for miniaturized components such as transistors 
very few things have changed the world as dramatically as the 
integrated circuit robert m white president of the national 
academy of engineering said in a statement the development of 
the integrated circuit was the singlemost important event that 
helped to usher in the information age 
since kilby and noyce pioneered the chip the 
informationprocessing capacity of a single chip has doubled about 
every three years 
