<TEXT>
ever since it was landscaped by jeanbaptiste 
colbert in 1667 the champs elysees has provided a dramatic setting 
for some of the nations most emotional events 
1792 the statue of king louis xv at the foot of the champs 
elysees was toppled and the site was renamed square of the 
revolution 
1793 a guillotine known as the national razor was 
erected especially for the beheading of king louis xvi and later 
queen marieantoinette charlotte corday and other victims of the 
reign of terror 
1829 a 75foot obelisk in pink granite and weighing more than 
220 tons was erected at what is now called the place de la concorde 
1885 victor hugos body lay in state for a night under the arc 
de triomphe shrouded in black crepe before the long funeral 
procession carrying his body from the champs to his burial at the 
pantheon 
1923 on nov 11 marking the fifth anniversary of the end of 
world war i the flame of remembrance was kindled for the first 
time over the tomb of the unknown soldier 
1944 gen charles de gaulle celebrating the liberation of 
paris from german occupation would describe the moment in his 
memoirs as coming face to face with the soul of a nation 
</TEXT>
