<DOCNO> AP900220-0196 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
protecting the champs elysees is not a new theme 
in his book champs elysees 17891989 jean aillaud recounts 
the story of the hotel massa the oldest private home on the champs 
in 1928 it was slated for demolition to make way for a 
multistory business center aillaud said in an interview but a 
group called friends of the champs elysees protested so 
vigorously it was taken down stone by stone and rebuilt on the 
left bank 
a host of other private homes and entertainment halls have not 
been so lucky replaced by airline offices automobile showrooms 
banks and movie theaters many of which are threatened today by 
soaring rents 
the only remaining villa is la paiva at no 25 built in 1865 
for the legendary polish courtesan of the same name who maintained 
a fashionable literary salon during the 19th century famous for 
its unique onyx staircase it has housed the travelers club since 
the early 1900s and can be visited by appointment 
</TEXT>
