<TEXT>
when roberto athayde wrote the play miss 
margaridas way in brazil 19 years ago it was forbidden to 
criticize government figures so he wrote about a schoolteacher 
athayde says audiences immediately identified his schoolteacher 
as the general who was then brazils dictator 
now dictators are falling but the author says the message of 
miss margaridas way is that they can also rise and people 
allow it to happen 
estelle parsons who is back in the role of miss margarida for 
its current revival on broadway agrees 
roberto said when he wrote it he wanted to show miss margarida 
had a tremendous amount of appeal people have to love dictators 
and perpetuate them and keep them going people are always saying 
how could this happen i thought this is how it happens 
onstage at the helen hayes theater parsons as miss margarida 
berates her eighthgrade class the audience if somebody comes in 
late she demands that they come to the stage and apologize they 
do 
she postures seduces fascinates she demands obedience 
punishes offenders and rants insanely theres no army backing her 
up but shes in control 
parsons who likes substance in the work she does first played 
