<TEXT>
alaska is a young frontier state where 
oldtimers still are called pioneers and being a pioneer has its 
benefits 
the state runs six bargainrate retirement homes pays residents 
65 and older 250 a month regardless of need provides them a 
propertytax exemption or rent rebate and issues free hunting and 
fishing licenses 
there also are local salestax exemptions free university 
tuition and free transportation on state ferries 
compared to other states alaska is generous to its elderly but 
that may not last the decade 
they are exacting a growing cost as alaskas population ages 
and a severe drop in oil revenues expected this decade already has 
led to changes in the most expensive programs 
the residency requirement for the 250amonth longevity 
bonus was increased from one to two years jan 1 and the 
legislature is considering phasing out the program over the next 
two decades and rates at the states pioneers homes were 
increased by as much as 52 percent recently 
after planning their retirement around the programs many older 
residents fear they may be left out in the street in their 
final years said barbara bathony director of the state pioneers 
benefits division 
it is traumatic for a person in their later years to have to 
think what is going to happen to me said joe alter of juneau 
a 74yearold retired civil engineer who moved to alaska 46 years 
ago when nobody thought of retiring here 
changes are inevitable said rep red boucher of anchorage who 
is 69 if changes are made carefully and over time he said senior 
citizens will adjust 
we treat them as good as any other state in the union if not 
better he said i think thats good we just have to achieve a 
balance in it i dont know of a single alaskan who wouldnt agree 
with that 
alaska began caring for its older residents long before it 
became a state in 1959 the first pioneers home opened in sitka in 
1913 
this year the state expects to spend more than 25 million to 
run the homes for about 540 residents 
more than double that amount is spent on the unique longevity 
bonus program created in 1972 to reward people who had helped 
settle the alaska territory at first it provided 100 a month to 
alaskans 65 and older who had lived in the state continuously for 
at least 25 years 
it started out as a great idea for those people who came here 
in hard times and made many sacrifices boucher said 
in 1984 however the alaska supreme court ruled the 25year 
residency rule unconstitutional the number of recipients and the 
programs cost increased sharply today more than 19000 alaskans 
claim the bonuses at a cost of about 62 million a year including 
administrative expenses 
proponents say that investment pays off economically and 
socially for many older alaskans the bonus helps them meet the 
states high cost of living 
theres a strong feeling that senior citizens want to become 
part of this society they dont want to be isolated alter said 
some of those benefits make it possible for these people to stay 
here economically otherwise theyd be going south 
when they leave they take their savings accounts their 
pensions and their retirement money out of state said connie 
sipe executive director of the state older alaskans commission 
the programs apparently have kept the elderly in alaska and 
brought in a few more the number of alaskans over 65 has grown at 
a rate faster than the overall population since 1970 according to 
the state labor department in 1988 those over 65 accounted for 38 
percent of alaskas population up from 23 percent in 1970 
we are having a little inmigration sipe said i dont 
think its because of the benefits i think its because of 
family 
even without transplants alaskas older population is expected 
to continue growing in the 1990s alaskans ages 5564 who soon 
will be signing up for longevity bonuses and beds in pioneers 
homes represent 54 percent of the population 
thats still a small percentage but they make up 15 to 20 
percent of the voting block making lawmakers reluctant to attack 
the programs publicly said rep terry martin of anchorage 
im not concerned because i dont think anythings going to 
happen right away said mellie terwilliger 80 an alaskan for 60 
years who lives with her husband in tok near their son and his 
family 
she said senior citizens have considerable political clout in 
juneau were very wellorganized 
martin favors basing the bonus on need a couple with a pair of 
pensions social security income and investments do not need an 
extra 500 a month from the state he said 
but sipe notes a 1984 study for the older alaskans commission 
which showed that half the longevity bonus recipients lived on 
10000 a year or less the study said 176 percent had incomes 
above 20000 
state sen jay kerttula a creator of the longevity bonus said 
it was not based on need because that would have made it seem like 
welfare lawmakers understood from their lifetime of experiences 
on the frontier what allowed a frontiersman to accept some type of 
assistance with some dignity kerttula said 
basing the bonus on need would require more bureaucracy and the 
increased costs would outweigh any savings said vera gazaway 
executive director of the nonprofit older persons action group 
inc in anchorage 
kerttula has proposed an annuity plan to replace state funding 
of the bonus an idea that has not yet become law 
state retirement homes also are becoming more costly 
pioneers homes are for those over 65 who have been continuous 
residents of alaska for at least 15 years however destitute 
alaskans get priority and do not have to meet the age limit 
onesixth of those in the homes at the end of 1989 were considered 
destitute 
the greatest demand is for beds in the nursingcare units where 
the wait can run to five years the rates up to 800 a month for 
nursing care compare with private nursing homes that charge more 
than 5000 a month 
the six homes are a major part of the elderly healthcare system 
in alaska there are no profitmaking nursing homes and only 12 
private nonprofit facilities all but one with fewer than 100 
beds 
the pioneers homes charge only those who can afford to pay and 
because of the restrictive residency requirements the homes do not 
get federal medicaid money bathony said that while costs have 
continued to rise the legislature has not increased the homes 
budget since 1986 
alaska needs a system for home care as an alternative to nursing 
homes sipe said legislation is pending that would allow the state 
to use medicaid money for home care 
were quite behind other states she said were in the 
bottom third in terms of homecare options for seniors 
