<TEXT>
it used to take the old ira man an hour to cross 
the room at a noraid fundraiser besieged as he was by people who 
wanted to shake his hand kiss his cheek or snap his picture 
this theyd tell their children is michael flannery the 
teenage soldier who fought the british in irelands war of 
independence the young man who moved to america but never forgot 
ireland the old man who founded irish northern aid to support the 
irish republican armys battle against british rule in northern 
ireland 
but when noraid held its annual dinner last month for the first 
time in 18 years michael flannery stayed home 
at 88 most people are inclined to ease off accepting easy 
acclaim and benign deference not flannery he has denounced the 
leaders of noraid and of sinn fein the iras political party for 
placing too much faith in politics and not enough in military force 
it grieved me to leave noraid because i was its founder he 
says in his squeaky brogue but it was the only thing my 
conscience would allow me to do 
for threequarters of a century flannerys conscience 
repeatedly has forced him to choose principle over expediency and 
to fight other irishmen over how to best fight the british 
on a recent morning flannery greeted a reporter at the door of 
his queens home his step once brisk now inclined toward a 
shuffle and his back once ramrod stiff was slightly hunched he 
sat on a piano bench in the living room folded his long thin 
hands on his lap and talked for two hours straight 
he began not a month a year or a decade ago but on easter 
1916 when irish nationalists rose against british rule he was a 
lanky 14yearold from tipperary who volunteered to run messages 
for the rebels 
the angloirish conflict ended in 1921 with a treaty giving 26 
of irelands 32 counties virtual independence as the predominantly 
roman catholic irish free state based in dublin but the six 
mostly protestant northeastern counties remained part of the united 
kingdom and civil war ensued in the south between those for and 
against the partition 
flannery joined the antitreaty ira faction led by eamon de 
valera and was captured and imprisoned for two years he saw 
several of his comrades executed in reprisal for ira attacks and 
he took part in a 39day hunger strike he left prison as bitter at 
dublin as he was at london 
de valera however formed a new political party in 1926 and led 
his supporters into the dublin parliament flannery meanwhile had 
moved to america he watched in horror as de valera rose to power 
and crushed the ira which still fought for a unified irish 
republic 
within four years de valera was arresting ira men flannery 
said four years after that he was executing them 
flannery settled in the new york city borough of queens with his 
wife got a job with an insurance company and joined irish athletic 
and cultural groups and he raised money for the ira 
the american irish lost interest in irelands intramural 
squabbles but flannery never gave up he claimed to have visited 
every saloon in new york city looking for donations even though he 
was a teetotaler a remnant of military discipline 
when a rising tide of violence against catholics in northern 
ireland revived the ira in the late 1960s flannery was ready 
again he faced a choice the official ira which decided to 
seek power politically or the provisional ira which took up 
arms in the north 
flannery threw in with the provos with a few other vets he 
founded noraid 
flannery insisted that the millions noraid collected went to the 
families of dead or imprisoned ira soldiers but in 1981 he was 
arrested on his way out of church and accused of banking an 
operation to smuggle guns to the ira 
at the trial flannery delivered his own opening statement we 
are indicted here for the love of freedom he said and the 
love of freedom alone 
even those opposed to the ira whose attacks often killed or 
maimed civilians were moved by such a durable passion although 
flannery and his codefendants essentially admitted the 
accusations they were found innocent and the next year flannery 
was elected grand marshal of the new york st patricks day parade 
but americas guns money and prayers did not resolve northern 
irelands troubles and in 1986 sinn fein declared itself willing 
to take seats in the dublin parliament a body from which militant 
nationalists had abstained since the islands partition to 
flannery this was official recognition of the government that had 
imprisoned him killed his comrades and sold out the north 
the ira sided with sinn fein as did most of noraids younger 
members flannery did not press the issue he continued to attend 
some noraid functions and noraid continued to use his name 
but last year a rift developed in noraid and flannery joined 
dissidents in accusing the organizations leaders of steering it 
toward politics and away from its original humanitarian 
objectives 
shortly thereafter he stood before noraids executive committee 
in a wedding hall in queens and accused sinn feins leaders of 
being free staters whose devotion to politics would soommunist party 
chief milos jakes 
the countrys first parliamentary elections in more than four 
decades are planned for june 8 
havel 53 who has said he is more interested in being a writer 
than president is popular among his countrymen and has not 
announced whether he will seek election in june 
havels government has insisted the soviet union withdraw its 
73500 troops as quickly as possible and favors eventual 
dissolution of the warsaw pact some czechoslovakian officials also 
have urged that nato be phased out something the bush 
administration strongly opposes 
