<TEXT>
companies with international operations may find 
it easier to set up a worldwide telephone and datatransmission 
network using a new digital phone service offered by atampt 
the phone company on monday demonstrated potential uses for the 
service which links the united states with japan and great britain 
using an international transmission standard a number of other 
nations are expected to be added to the network by the end of the 
year 
the service can be dialed up like a regular phone call once a 
special digital line is installed to the customer american 
telephone amp telegraph co said 
unlike conventional analog phone lines digital lines enable the 
transmission of computer data and video conferences they also 
provide distortionfree phone calls and far faster fax 
transmissions overseas 
atampt began offering dialup digital lines to other nations in 
1988 but these lines are based on a north american standard which 
transmits data at 56 kilobits per second most of the rest of the 
world uses digital lines that transmit data at 64 kilobits per 
second 
a kilobit is 1000 bits a bit is the smallest piece of 
information used by a computer and represents either the digit 1 
or 0 
the difference in standards has meant us customers must use an 
adaptor to send computerbased information abroad which creates 
the possiblity that errors could be introduced in the transmission 
said atampt spokesman rick wallerstein 
with the new service which was announced last month a us 
company could set up a phone and datatransmission network around 
the world based on the 64kilobit standard 
before the dialup digital services were available the only way 
for a company to send computer data overseas was through a leased 
private line these dedicated lines are more expensive in 
general than the dialup services which are billed per minute of 
use like conventional phone lines 
the new switched digital international service was approved feb 
5 by the federal communications commission 
the service to japan is provided in cooperation with nippon 
telegraph and telephone corp and overseas communications japan 
while the british service is a venture with british telecom plc 
at a news conference monday atampt demonstrated a video 
conference hookup with tokyo using two of the new phone lines 
simultaneously because video transmissions contain a huge amount 
of data their quality is improved by sending it over two lines at 
once 
but the picture quality still is lower than what is provided by 
normal television broadcasts the image is grainy and the motion is 
delayed giving the impression that the video is being shown in 
slow motion 
the equipment used for the video conference is made by 
picturetel corp of peabody mass which has a marketing agreement 
with atampt 
atampt also demonstrated a personal computer linkup through the 
phone lines when changes were made on a computer screen in new 
york they could be seen on a similar computer screen in tokyo by 
watching the tv monitor used for the video conference 
in addition atampt demonstrated a digital telephone which 
provides far higher quality voice transmission than conventional 
phones and an optical scanner that allows the user to scan 
documents or objects electronically then send them over the phone 
lines abroad where they appear on a computer screen 
nippon telegraph and telephone also demonstrated computer and 
video hookups over the new phone lines 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
