<DOCNO> AP900220-0226 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court today refused to bar 
national banks from selling mortgages in the form of passthrough 
certificates a practice the securities industry says violates 
federal banking law 
the court without comment let stand a ruling that such sales 
are legal 
federal law allows national banks to sell the conventional real 
estate mortgages they hold but generally prohibits banks from 
underwriting buying and selling securities 
banks traditionally have sold longterm mortgages for other 
revenue sources and an increasingly popular means of selling 
mortages is the use of passthrough certificates which are 
securities 
the buyer of such a certificate obtains an interest in a pool of 
the banks conventional mortgages rather than a single mortgage 
the californiabased security pacific national bank began 
selling mortgage passthrough certificates in 1987 with a 194 
million public offering with the securities and exchange commission 
the securities industry association a group of more than 500 
organizations that account for over 90 percent of the nations 
securities brokerage and investment banking business asked federal 
regulators about the validity of passthrough certificates 
the comptroller of the currency concluded that security 
pacifics passthrough certificate program was authorized under 
the national banking laws which he said does not restrict the 
means by which national banks may sell or transfer interests in 
their mortgages 
the comptrollers decision was in keeping with the recent trend 
toward deregulation of the banking industry with the courts and 
federal regulators obliterating legal barriers between the banking 
industry and other forms of commerce 
after the comptrollers decision on security pacifics sales of 
passthrough certificates the securities industry association sued 
in federal court the suit sought to stop what the association 
asserted is the illegal sales of securities 
us district judge kevin duffy of new york city ruled in 1988 
that selling passthrough certificates amounted to underwriting 
securities in violation of a 1933 federal banking law the 
glasssteagall act 
but the 2nd us circuit court of appeals last sept 8 reversed 
duffys ruling and agreed with the comptroller of the currency 
the appeals court said such sales constitute the business of 
banking and not the business of dealing in securities and stock 
in the appeal acted on today lawyers for the securities 
industry association said the effect of the 2nd circuit courts 
ruling is to write glasssteagall right out of the statute 
books 
in a friendofthecourt brief supporting the appeal 
lawyers for the investment company institute said the appeals court 
ruling has allowed the underwriting of mortgagebacked securities 
directly by national banks 
the decision simply demolishes the glasssteagall act they 
said 
the bush administration and lawyers for the security pacific 
national bank urged the court to reject the appeal 
the case is securities industry association vs clarke 89748 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

