<TEXT>
federal reserve chairman alan greenspan said 
today the economy has likely passed the danger point for an 
imminent recession and he predicted continued although modest 
economic growth for the rest of this year 
greenspan said the central bank expects the economy to grow far 
more sluggishly this year than the bush administration predicts 
that scenario could dash the administrations hopes of making 
significant progress on reducing the federal budget deficit 
greenspan commented in an annual appearance before congress to 
reveal the banks allimportant monetary and economic growth 
targets for the new year 
the testimony bolstered the belief among many private economists 
that the federal reserve board is not likely to move soon to push 
interest rates lower 
following greenspans testimony prices tumbled in the stock and 
bond markets in midday trading that analysts said reflected 
investor worries about rising interest rates worldwide 
on wall street the dow jones industrial average of 30 stocks 
was down 4257 points to 259302 at 2 pm est in the credit 
markets the bellwether 30year treasury bond was off by about 
1250 per 1000 in face value with its yield rising to 863 
percent from 846 percent late friday 
greenspan emphasized a belief that the economy appears to be 
rebounding from an extremely sluggish octoberdecember period while 
at the same time inflationary pressures remain at unacceptable 
levels 
the fed chairman cited a string of recent economic reports 
showing a rebound in economic activity in january ranging from 
rising auto sales to a big jump in housing construction 
from these and similar data one can infer the beginnings of a 
modest firming in economic activity greenspan told a house 
banking subcommittee 
while we cannot be certain that we are as yet out of the 
recessionary woods such evidence warrants at least guarded 
optimism he said available indicators of nearterm 
economic performance suggest that the weakest point may have 
passed 
greenspans testimony served to reaffirm statements he made 
three weeks ago in another congressional appearance 
the feds economic forecast showed that the central bank is 
looking for the economy as measured by the gross national product 
to grow at an anemic rate of between 175 percent and 2 percent 
this year 
that is far below the administrations projection that the 
economy will grow by 26 percent this year when measured from the 
fourth quarter of 1989 
the administration is pinning its hopes of cutting the federal 
budget deficit in half on a belief that economic growth will 
rebound significantly in 1990 from the depressed level in the 
fourth quarter when the gnp rose at an annual rate of just 05 
percent its poorest showing in 3 years 
but if as appears likely the fed pursues a tighter credit 
policy to dampen inflationary pressures then interest rates will 
be higher than the administration is forecasting and growth will be 
slower two developments that will add billions of dollars to the 
budget deficit 
the feds economic forecast for 1990 represented only a modest 
change from a preliminary estimate the central bank made last june 
when it forecast growth of 15 percent to 2 percent 
however the fed substantially lowered its inflation estimate to 
4 percent to 45 percent for consumer prices down from a june 
forecast of 45 percent to 5 percent signaling perhaps a renewed 
emphasis on getting prices lower 
greenspan said that while consumer prices for january scheduled 
to be reported wednesday would show a sizable jump due to energy 
and food costs a reversal of this temporary spurt is apparently 
under way 
the ultimate objective of economic policy is to foster the 
maximum sustainable rate of economic growth greenspan said 
adding that inflation insidiously undermines business and 
consumer confidence in the economys future course 
greenspans testimony tracked the expectations of many 
economists who believe that the fed is succeeding in attempts to 
engineer a soft landing for the economy in which growth slows 
enough to dampen inflation but not enough to end the 7yearlong 
economic recovery 
but analysts said greenspans testimony sets the stage for a 
possible clash between the administrations optimistic economic 
goals and a fed intent on keeping a damper on growth to make sure 
that inflation does not get out of hand 
the public comments from the administration will be coming hot 
and heavy later on this year as bush officials try to nudge the fed 
into an easier stance predicted david jones chief economist of 
aubrey g lanston amp co a government securities dealer 
economists said a spurt in prices at the beginning of the year 
caused in large part by unusually cold weather which pushed up food 
costs also was working against lower interest rates 
the fed does not want to be perceived as easing at a time when 
inflation is accelerating even if those inflationary pressures 
were considered to be temporary jones said 
</TEXT>
