investigating a former employees allegations that the 
longdistance company obtained confidential information about 
competitors when it bid successfully for part of a 25 billion 
government contract 
sprint officials said the allegations first arose in august 
during an exit interview for a sprint salesman in the washington 
area whose job was eliminated during a restructuring 
spokesman syd courson in kansas city where sprint is based 
said the company investigated the allegations and found no evidence 
of wrongdoing 
courson said the former employee made broad allegations that 
sprint employees had obtained and used other longdistance 
companies confidential information when preparing sprints bid for 
the fts 2000 communications contract 
sprint the nations thirdlargest supplier of longdistance 
service won 40 percent of the giant contract industry leader atampt 
won the majority 
we chalked it up to a disgruntled employee a former 
employee courson said 
sprints internal investigation was completed in october but 
resumed later in the year after allegations assumed to be by the 
same person that sprint had tapped into the general services 
administration computer courson said 
in october a sprint employee in the washington area was 
contacted by the fbi courson said three other employees and an 
outside consultant who had worked for sprint were contacted in late 
january about the allegations 
we then contacted the fbi and told them of our findings and 
offered them various documents courson said we want to 
cooperate fully on this and get it behind us thats essentially 
where it stands 
