<TEXT>
officials of eastern airlines met tuesday with 
major creditors in an effort to reach agreement on a new plan for 
its bankruptcy reorganization 
easterns exclusive right to file such a plan was due to expire 
at midnight unless the federal bankruptcy court granted the airline 
another extension 
representatives of the airline and its creditors continued to 
meet late tuesday and planned to extend the discussions into 
wednesday said karen ceremsak a spokeswoman for eastern at its 
headquarters in miami she declined to provide further details 
ms ceremsak said it appeared unlikely that eastern would 
request an extension of tuesdays end to its exclusive period 
because creditors were negotiating with eastern and unlikely to 
file their own reorganization plan 
creditors attorneys and other representatives couldnt be 
reached for comment 
last monday us bankruptcy judge burton r lifland granted 
easterns request for an eightday extension to tuesday of the 
deadline for filing its reorganization plan on an exclusive basis 
during that time other parties such as creditors cannot submit 
competing proposals 
lifland extended the deadline after several parties in the 
proceeding said progress had been made toward agreement on a plan 
eastern has been restructuring under bankruptcy court 
supervision since a bitter strike began last march 4 
david i shapiro the courtappointed examiner overseeing 
easterns chapter 11 proceeding supported easterns request last 
week for an extension and told lifland that substantial 
progress is being made in negotiations between the airline and 
its creditors 
the committee representing unsecured creditors also supported 
easterns petition 
even representatives of preferred shareholders who recently 
advocated liquidation or outright sale of eastern supported the 
airlines request for more time 
the preferred shareholders had criticized easterns latest 
reorganization proposal which proposes to pay them no more than 10 
cents on the dollar in the form of new stock 
easterns latest plan also calls for paying unsecured creditors 
only 10 percent of their debts in cash when the airline emerges 
from bankruptcy protection and 70 percent more over the following 
10 years without interest 
in return for accepting partial repayment easterns parent 
texas air corp would give the unsecured creditors 40 percent of 
easterns equity 
lawyers representing the air line pilots association and the 
machinists union have opposed easterns requests for extensions of 
the deadline 
last weeks extension was the fourth granted by lifland since 
the bankruptcy proceeding began last march 9 
the eastern pilots and flight attendants abandoned their 
sympathy strikes just before thanksgiving but eastern had rebuilt 
as a smaller carrier and hired mostly nonunion workers to replace 
the strikers the machinists union remains on strike against the 
carrier 
